<span id="freeTextContainer10187585790749469544">This book is a total slog. The Goodreads description calls it meticulous; I call it boring. It kind of lands in gray area between fiction and non-fiction, and it&apos;s pretty obvious that neither Mailer nor Schiller (the principal &quot;researcher&quot;/journalist/producer/opportunist) actually did a face-to-face interview with Gilmore.<br/>As a subject, Gilmore just isn&apos;t that interesting. One of the journalists suggests that Gilmore is &quot;mediocrity enlarged by history,&quot; and that pretty much sums it up. He was a m</span>
  <span id="freeText10187585790749469544" style="display:none">This book is a total slog. The Goodreads description calls it meticulous; I call it boring. It kind of lands in gray area between fiction and non-fiction, and it's pretty obvious that neither Mailer nor Schiller (the principal "researcher"/journalist/producer/opportunist) actually did a face-to-face interview with Gilmore.<br />As a subject, Gilmore just isn't that interesting. One of the journalists suggests that Gilmore is "mediocrity enlarged by history," and that pretty much sums it up. He was a mediocre criminal and an awful human being. Had he ended up with life in prison, rather than a death sentence, no one would written ten words about him.<br />I can't believe this won a Pulitzer.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10187585790749469544" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
