<div id="review_74007101" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/74007101" />
    <a title="Flavia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1742354-flavia"><img alt="Flavia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1233329351p2/1742354.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/74007101?book_show_action=true">Oct 09, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Flavia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Flavia" href="/user/show/1742354-flavia">Flavia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer74007101" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1881803940334349582">I had this book on my list as &quot;must-read classic&quot;. I don&apos;t know where that came from. It was one of the most boring books I ever read. I cannot believe I ploughed through &gt; 1,000 pages of excrutiatingly detailed narration of the true crimes, trial and execution of Gary Gilmore. I didn&apos;t give anything away; it&apos;s on the book jacket. After reading how each person dressed, how they were raised (even the minor players whose names you can forget right afterwards!), their exact words in every exact cir</span>
  <span id="freeText1881803940334349582" style="display:none">I had this book on my list as "must-read classic". I don't know where that came from. It was one of the most boring books I ever read. I cannot believe I ploughed through &gt; 1,000 pages of excrutiatingly detailed narration of the true crimes, trial and execution of Gary Gilmore. I didn't give anything away; it's on the book jacket. After reading how each person dressed, how they were raised (even the minor players whose names you can forget right afterwards!), their exact words in every exact circumstance, the trial and the legalities of the appeals.... I feel I didn't learn much about the US court system, except that it is convoluted. Nor could I really care about any of the "characters". I think it is unlikely to change the minds of those in favor of the death penalty, if that was the intent. Bottom line is: what was the point of this, exactly?</span>
  <a data-text-id="1881803940334349582" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


