  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2474489299" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2474489299" />
    <a title="Daniel Villines" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2266055-daniel-villines"><img alt="Daniel Villines" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1536179787p2/2266055.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2474489299?book_show_action=true">Nov 17, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Daniel Villines" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Daniel Villines" href="/user/show/2266055-daniel-villines">Daniel Villines</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2474489299" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9556313243170302673">As indicated by the title, <i>The Executioner&apos;s Song</i> is primarily about capital punishment. It raises the serious and thoughtful question as to whether or not society should be killing those it deems to be undesirable. After all, we enter into a covenant with society and agree to give up certain freedoms in exchange for certain protections, and the protection of life could be considered one of society’s fundamental duties. And yet, society regularly takes the life of some of those that break the la</span>
  <span id="freeText9556313243170302673" style="display:none">As indicated by the title, <i>The Executioner's Song</i> is primarily about capital punishment. It raises the serious and thoughtful question as to whether or not society should be killing those it deems to be undesirable. After all, we enter into a covenant with society and agree to give up certain freedoms in exchange for certain protections, and the protection of life could be considered one of society’s fundamental duties. And yet, society regularly takes the life of some of those that break the laws within which we are entwined. There appears to be a dire inconsistency between what society promises and what society delivers.<br /><br /><i>The Executioner's Song</i> is a book that forces its readers, its societal members, to look directly at our responsibility. Mailer puts the gun to the heart of the condemned man and asks us to pull the trigger without all of the decades-long, feel-good motions associated with the due process of law. With appeals and judicial reviews, we are allowed to wallow in the law and, if not feel good, then at least feel nothing or think nothing of society’s underlying responsibility. In fact, fighting a death sentence over the course of many years may degrade the question down to a win-lose proposition where winning is actually an abandonment of society’s responsibility. <br /><br />And beyond the big esoteric issue, there is the condemned man, Gary Gilmore. If anyone could be a poster boy for unredemptive criminality, it’s Gilmore. Crime, including murder, is an urge. It sits in front of Gary Gilmore as an equally considered response to the stresses that life regularly imposes on all of us.<br /><br />And yet, he's still human in the quiet times that make up most of life. Gilmore is an artist by talent, he knows the soul-entwining feeling of love, he is aware that knowledge exists outside of his own perceptions, and he genuinely connects with those that he comes to know. The big esoteric issue becomes a human issue, and a personal issue. No human is purely evil just as no human is purely good. Therefore, the question of killing the good parts of a person must be considered even though it is often and conveniently ignored. <br /><br />Finally, in consideration of vengeance, the ability to perform a lynching by the revenge-filled family member was exceedingly easier than it is today. 100-200 years ago, society needed to provide and enforce an alternative to lynchings in order to preserve the rule-of-law. This simply cannot be an issue today. Custodial measures to prevent such acts have been developed and compounded to the point that busting out an accused killer is practically impossible. Thoughts of such an act would be met with thoughts of futility before thoughts of plausibility. Furthermore, the act of freeing a criminal with the intent to affect revenge has moved beyond the acceptance of society. And if one truly wants revenge, stepping outside the door one morning while thinking of the killer never stepping outside of a 6’ x 8’ cell in such a fashion for the remainder of his life is vengeance. When asked if there are fates worse than death, Gilmore replied, "I think to make somebody go on living in a lessened state of existence, I think that could be worse than killing ’em."<br /><br />Aside from the substantial issues this book brings to mind, the writing was somewhat overdone. Mailer must find it impossible to let any detail, no matter how inconsequential, to be left unwritten. As such, we get intimate details of the lives of every character, from those that drive the plot to those that may appear and disappear without affecting any key event whatsoever. And this type of exhaustive writing is applied to trivial events as well. The reason why this book is over a thousand pages long is not because the story required a thousand pages to tell, but rather because Mailer could not resist writing about everything. The effect is somewhat exhausting.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9556313243170302673" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review2474489299">
