  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2000500450" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2000500450" />
    <a title="d.a.v.i.d" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67794375-d-a-v-i-d"><img alt="d.a.v.i.d" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616351021p2/67794375.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2000500450?book_show_action=true">May 15, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="d.a.v.i.d" class="user" itemprop="url" name="d.a.v.i.d" href="/user/show/67794375-d-a-v-i-d">d.a.v.i.d</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2000500450" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3225660475631085676">The law, and the randomness of it, geographically and demographically, has always disturbed me. Additionally, the comingling of it from disparate precedents only exacerbates it, and the courtroom turns itself into a &quot;Wheel of Fortune.&quot;<br/><br/>Money is made by layering one brick of precepts on top of another. What you end up with is an expensive wall without doors, made poorly and soon to crumble. There is a way out but only for the officers of jurisprudence and their fraternity. If you want to leave wit</span>
  <span id="freeText3225660475631085676" style="display:none">The law, and the randomness of it, geographically and demographically, has always disturbed me. Additionally, the comingling of it from disparate precedents only exacerbates it, and the courtroom turns itself into a "Wheel of Fortune."<br /><br />Money is made by layering one brick of precepts on top of another. What you end up with is an expensive wall without doors, made poorly and soon to crumble. There is a way out but only for the officers of jurisprudence and their fraternity. If you want to leave with them, there is a fee to be free, and no guarantee.<br /><br />Yes, Mailer is quite the writer. And the story is well told.<br /><br />However, there is little pleasure gained from someone else's misery nor do I like reading how one person can dismantle and destroy the lives of many. Gary Gilmore, a deplorable celebrity, would be a non-issue in todays' world, a paragraph on page three of a local rag. So, what have we learned from his crime and his defense decades later? Does the legal and prison systems work? No, but business is brisk, dockets and prisons are full, and it continues to aggrandize. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="3225660475631085676" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

